    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Here I will create some initial thoughts on how the process of setting up
an Octopress blog is, specifically when hosting it on my personal
<a href="https://dantrim.github.io">github pages website</a>.</p>

<h2 id="setting-up-the-repository-and-setting-up-octopress">Setting Up the Repository and Setting Up Octopress</h2>

<p>After upgrading my laptop and OS to <code>macOS Catalina</code> (<code>v10.15</code>) I found that some
of the steps were not working, at least not as I remember.
It has been several months since I last toyed around with this blog.</p>

<h3 id="ruby-version">Ruby Version</h3>

<p>I found that the latest version of Ruby did not seem to work, at least when I was using
Ruby <code>v3.0.0</code> that was installed with <code>brew install ruby</code> on my new laptop. Following the setup
steps on the <a href="http://octopress.org/docs/setup/">Octopress docs page</a> for installing the dependencies,
I found that the <code>bundle install</code> step would always fail.
Given that I am not an expert with Ruby (nor do I ever really care to be),
the errors were a bit confusing.
I figured that it no longer worked, compared to my older laptop&#39;s setup,
given the newer version of Ruby (and all of the associated packages).</p>

<p>Using <a href="https://github.com/rbenv/rbenv">rbenv</a> which appears to be similar
to Python&#39;s <a href="https://github.com/pyenv/pyenv">pyenv</a>, I installed an earlier version
of Ruby, version <code>2.6.5</code>:
<figure class='code'><figcaption> <a href='http://dantrim.github.io/downloads/code/2020-06-05/setup_ruby.sh' target='_blank'>download</a></figcaption>
<div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nb">export </span><span class="nv">PATH</span><span class="o">=</span>~/.rbenv/shims:/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:<span class="k">${</span><span class="nv">PATH</span><span class="k">}</span> <span class="c"># in ~/.bash_profile</span>
</span><span class='line'>rbenv install 2.6.5
</span><span class='line'>rbenv <span class="nb">local </span>2.6.5
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></p>

<h3 id="setting-up-for-writing-source">Setting Up for Writing Source</h3>

<p>Once the adequate version of Ruby is made available (following the discussion
<a href="#ruby-version">above</a>), I follow the steps listed below for a complete and
fresh checkout and install of the blog:
<figure class='code'><figcaption> <a href='http://dantrim.github.io/downloads/code/2020-06-05/setup_env.sh' target='_blank'>download</a></figcaption>
<div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>git clone <a href="https://github.com/dantrim/dantrim.github.io">https://github.com/dantrim/dantrim.github.io</a>
</span><span class='line'><span class="nb">cd </span>dantrim.github.io
</span><span class='line'>git checkout <span class="nb">source</span>
</span><span class='line'>gem install bundler
</span><span class='line'>rbenv <span class="nb">local </span>2.6.5 <span class="c"># setup the tested ruby version via rbenv</span>
</span><span class='line'>bundle install
</span><span class='line'>rake install
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>
At this point, calling <code>rake new_post[&quot;&lt;name&gt;&quot;]</code> should succeed.</p>

<h2 id="writing-new-blog-posts">Writing New Blog Posts</h2>

<p>In order to get setup with writing a new blog post, the following sequence looks
to be sufficient:
<figure class='code'><figcaption> <a href='http://dantrim.github.io/downloads/code/2020-06-05/start_writing_post.sh' target='_blank'>download</a></figcaption>
<div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>rake new_post<span class="o">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;&lt;post title&gt;&quot;</span><span class="o">]</span>
</span><span class='line'>rake generate
</span><span class='line'>rake watch
</span><span class='line'>rake preview <span class="c"># in second shell, blog available at <a href="http://localhost:4000/">http://localhost:4000/</a></span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></p>

<h2 id="deploying-blog-entries-after-a-fresh-clone">Deploying Blog Entries after a Fresh Clone</h2>

<p>If you checkout your blog&#39;s repository in a new location (e.g.
a new directory or a new machine), you will first need to sync
up the <code>_deploy</code> directory with the remote&#39;s <code>master</code> branch
before running <code>rake deploy</code>. Run the following steps to achieve
this:
<figure class='code'><figcaption> <a href='http://dantrim.github.io/downloads/code/2020-06-05/update_deploy.sh' target='_blank'>download</a></figcaption>
<div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
<span class='line-number'>9</span>
<span class='line-number'>10</span>
<span class='line-number'>11</span>
<span class='line-number'>12</span>
<span class='line-number'>13</span>
<span class='line-number'>14</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="c">#!/bin/bash</span>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>git clone <a href="mailto:git@github.com">git@github.com</a>:&lt;repo&gt;.git
</span><span class='line'><span class="nb">cd</span> &lt;repo&gt;
</span><span class='line'>git checkout <span class="nb">source</span> <span class="c"># source is the working branch</span>
</span><span class='line'>mkdir _deploy
</span><span class='line'><span class="nb">cd </span>_deploy
</span><span class='line'>git init
</span><span class='line'>git remote add origin <a href="mailto:git@github.com">git@github.com</a>:&lt;repo&gt;.git
</span><span class='line'>git pull origin master <span class="c"># master is the public view of the blog</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="nb">cd</span> ..
</span><span class='line'><span class="c"># make changes under source/_posts/</span>
</span><span class='line'>rake generate
</span><span class='line'>rake deploy
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>
More information can be found on the <a href="http://octopress.org/docs/deploying/github/">Octopress deploy docs</a>.</p>

<h2 id="other-misc-changes">Other Misc Changes</h2>

<h3 id="updating-the-code-formatting-functions">Updating the code formatting functions</h3>

<p>I have found, also, that using the <code>include_code</code> blocks are apparently
the cleanest way to get code to be formatted. Though I have made
some modifications.</p>

